{{about|the waterbody|the town|Batemans Bay}} {{Use Australian English|date=May 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} {{Infobox body of water | name = Batemans Bay | other_name = | image = Batemans Bay Aerial.JPG | alt = | caption = Aerial photo, looking west, 2008. | image_bathymetry = | alt_bathymetry = | caption_bathymetry = | location = [[South Coast (New South Wales)|South Coast]], [[New South Wales]] | coords = {{coord|35|44|S|150|13|E|region:AU-NSW_type:waterbody_source:gns|display=inline,title}} | type = Bay | inflow = [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]] | outflow = [[Tasman Sea]], [[South Pacific Ocean]] | catchment = {{convert|28|km2|abbr=on}} | basin_countries = [[Australia]] | date-built = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent bodies of water --> | date-flooded = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} For man-made and other recent bodies of water --> | agency = | length = | width = | area = {{convert|34.5|km2|abbr=on}} | depth = {{convert|11.1|m|ft|abbr=on}} | max-depth = | volume = {{convert|383484|ML}} | residence_time = | shore = | elevation = | frozen = ''never'' | islands = Snapper Island, Tollgate Islands | cities = [[Batemans Bay]] | reference = <ref name=environ>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/estuaries/stats/BatemansBay.htm|title=Batemans Bay: Physical characteristics|work=Coastal and floodplain management: Coastal zone management: Estuaries of NSW|publisher=NSW Environment & Heritage|date=26 April 2012|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> }} '''Batemans Bay''' is an open [[bay|oceanic embayment]] that is located in the [[South Coast (New South Wales)|South Coast]] region of [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]]. The bay forms the [[river mouth|mouth]] of the [[Clyde River (New South Wales)|Clyde River]] and its primary outflow is to the [[Tasman Sea]] of the [[South Pacific Ocean]].
==Location and features== Batemans Bay is fed by the Clyde River and its tributaries, drawing its catchment from the eastern slopes of the [[Budawang Range]] and the [[Great Dividing Range]] from within the [[Budawang National Park|Budawang]], [[Clyde River National Park|Clyde River]], [[Bimberamala National Park|Bimberamala]], and [[Monga National Park|Monga]] national parks.<ref name=bonzle>{{cite web|title=Map of Batemans Bay, NSW|url=http://www.bonzle.com/c/a?a=p&p=37208&cmd=sp|work=Bonzle Digital Atlas of Australia|year=2013|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref><ref name=gnb>{{NSW GNR|id=anKqZxUl|title=Batemans Bay|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> Cullendulla Creek also flows into Batemans Bay, between the townships of Surfside and Longbeach, west of Square Head.<ref name=ATSILEP />
The total catchment area of the bay is approximately {{convert|28|km2}} and the bay holds an estimated {{convert|383484|ML}} of water at an average depth of {{convert|11.1|m}}. The surface area of the bay comprises {{convert|34.5|km2}}<ref name=environ /> and generally stretches from the [[confluence]] of the Clyde River with the bay east of the town of Batemans Bay, near Snapper Island; to its mouth with the Tasman Sea at the Tollgate Islands, located between North Head and Circuit Beach.
==History== The traditional custodians of the land surrounding Batemans Bay are the [[Indigenous Australians|Indigenous Australian]] [[Yuin people]] of the Walbunja clan. A number of sites surrounding the bay are considered culturally significant to the Aboriginal peoples.<ref name=ATSILEP>{{cite web|title=Hanging Rock Catalina |work=Preliminary Public Aboriginal Heritage Inventory |publisher=[[Eurobodalla Shire Council]] |date=April 2009 |accessdate=25 May 2013 |url=http://www.esc.nsw.gov.au/site/AboriginalHeritageStudy/pdf/stage4/Part%201.pdf |format=PDF }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
On 22 April 1770, European explorer, [[James Cook|Captain James Cook]] first sighted the bay when navigating his way around Australia on his ship, [[HMS Endeavour|HMS ''Endeavour'']]. Cook may have named the bay in honour of Nathaniel Bateman; the captain of [[HMS Northumberland (1750)|HMS ''Northumberland'']] at the time when Cook was serving as her master from 1760-62.<ref name=gnb /><ref name="InletEludedBass">{{cite web|last=Moore|first=Dennis|year=2002|url= http://www.southcoast.com.au/batemansbay/bassinlet/index.html|title=The Inlet That Eluded Bass, Batemans Bay - South Coast NSW|publisher=Morningside Internet|accessdate=25 May 2013}}</ref> Alternatively, the name was chosen in honour of [[John Bateman, 2nd Viscount Bateman]], a former [[Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty]] in the 1750s.<ref>{{cite book |title =Captain Cook's War and Peace | first =John | last =Robson | coauthors= | month = | year =2009 | publisher =University of New South Wales Press | page=107 | url = | isbn =9781742231099}}</ref>
