{{Infobox ecoregion |name = |image = Forest, Santa Criz Dept, Bolivia.jpg |image_size = |image_alt = |caption = |map_size = |map_alt = |map_caption = |biogeographic_realm = [[Neotropical realm|Neotropical]] |biome = [[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests]] – [[Amazon biome|Amazon]] |animals = |bird_species = |mammal_species = |border = |borders = |area = |country = [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]] |elevation = |coordinates = {{coord| -15|-62|region:BR|display=it}} |geology = |rivers = |climate = |soil = |conservation = |global200 = |habitat_loss = |habitat_loss_ref = |protected = |protected_ref = }} The '''Chiquitano dry forests''' is a [[tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|tropical dry broadleaf forest]] [[ecoregion]] in [[Bolivia]] and [[Brazil]].
==Setting== {{location map|Bolivia|relief=yes|lat_deg= -15|lon_deg=-62|caption=Location in Bolivia|width=220px}} The Chiquitano dry forests cover an area of {{convert|230,600|km2|sqmi|sp=us}}. The ecoregion lies east of the [[Andes]] in the lowlands of eastern Bolivia and the Brazilian states of [[Mato Grosso]] and [[Rondônia]].
The [[World Wildlife Fund]] includes the Chiquitano dry forests in the [[Amazon biome]].{{sfn|Intro: Amazon Ecoregions and Ecology – Yale}} The ecoregion adjoins the [[Dry Chaco]] ecoregion to the south and the [[Pantanal]] ecoregion to the southeast. To the northeast it blends into the [[Cerrado]] ecoregion. To the northwest it adjoins the [[Madeira-Tapajós moist forests]] and [[Southwest Amazon moist forests]] ecoregions.{{sfn|WildFinder – WWF}}
===Climate=== The climate of the Chiquitano dry forests is [[tropical]], with a strong dry season during the southern hemisphere winter.
