'''Reactive sulfur species''' (RSS) are a family of sulfur-based chemical compounds that can oxidize and inhibit thiol-proteins and enzymes. They are often formed by the oxidation of Thiols and disulfides into higher oxidation states. Examples of RSS include [[persulfide]]s, [[polysulfide]]s and [[thiosulfate]].<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_January_28_2016c">{{cite journal |title= Reactive sulfur species: an emerging concept in oxidative stress |pmid=12033429 | doi=10.1515/BC.2002.042 |volume=383 |pages=375-88 | last1 = Giles | first1 = GI | last2 = Jacob | first2 = C | journal=Biol Chem}}</ref><ref name="MyUser_Nature.com_January_28_2016c">{{cite journal |url=http://www.nature.com/nchembio/journal/v11/n7/full/nchembio.1834.html |title=Biogenesis of reactive sulfur species for signaling by hydrogen sulfide oxidation pathways |journal=Nature Chemical Biology |author= |accessdate= January 28, 2016 |volume=11|doi= 10.1038/nchembio.1834|pmc=4818113}}</ref>

